stylometry: In our group project, we looked at data from the Professional Development here at LEC. We were trying to figure out how many people would have to come to summer classes to 1) break even and 2) make a profit. We decided to use a break even analysis to do this. We looked at how many catalogs were mailed to people needing to take classes. We then used goal seek to find what response rate we would need to cover the total costs of the courses (these included online costs, teachers saleries). I believe after mailing 600 catalogs, we needed a response of 3.77% to break even. We also decided to run it to make a profit of over $90,000. Again, after mailing 600 catalogs, we would need a response rate of over 11% to accomplish this profit. I learned from this that in any business situation, you can run a model like this to determine what you need to make a profit or break even. It is a very useful tool moving forward in the business world.
